FIGHTING
On the Field
Heavy fighting is where I test myself most honestly. Rapier kept me moving when injury changed what heavy could look like.
Heavy Fighting
Armored combat is where I found discipline, challenge, distance control, timing, and the kind of growth that has to be earned shot by shot.
Rapier During Recovery
In 2025, ankle injuries changed my heavy fighting year. I kept going through rapier, staying on the field while healing and continuing to learn.
What Fighting Taught Me
Confidence is not the absence of doubt. It is stepping in anyway, learning from better fighters, and coming back again after every hard day.
THE CHIV HUNT
A Tangible Goal
The Chiv Hunt was never just a number. It was a structure for growth: go find the best fighters you can, ask for the lessons, and keep showing up.
2024 Hunt
In 2024, I set myself a tangible goal and pursued members of the Order of Chivalry across the Known World. I fought 123 different knights, usually aiming for three or more fights with each whenever possible. The hunt became the record for most fought in a single hunt and tied for fastest completion.
	•	123 different knights in 2024
	•	Across multiple kingdoms in the Known World
	•	Built around learning, not just collecting names
2025 Continuation
Ankle injuries changed the pace of 2025, but not the path. I still fought 47 members of the Order of Chivalry, did rapier while injured, and began helping with the Chiv Hunt Facebook page. The record mattered, but the lessons mattered more.
Every signature represents a fight, a lesson, and one more step on the path.
STORIES
Stories Behind the Work
These are not just objects or posts. They are friendships, memorials, celebrations, distractions that kept me moving, and the proof that art belongs on my path too.
Art Story
Kahlan’s Knighting Glass
Before War of the Wings in 2022 and 2023, I came in second to Kahlan in the Iron Rose. She was one of my favorite fighters to measure myself against. When she was announced for knighthood, I could not travel to Trimaris, so I decided to make a glass as a celebration gift and bring it to War of the Wings.
I started posting tiny hints while I worked: the foot of the horse, a line, a shape. It kept me laughing while I made it. It also gave my brain somewhere to go during a difficult time in my life. Some projects are art. Some are survival. Sometimes they are both.
￼
A glass made to celebrate Kahlan’s knighting — a gift, a challenge, and one of the projects that helped keep my spirits up.
Art Story
The Laurel Glass
This glass was made for Jennifer Caudipteryx when she was elevated to the Laurel. I said in the post that I would not have made it through some hard things without her support, including the chaos of rehoming my cats. She represents what it means to be a peer: art, dedication, steadiness, and kindness.
Making that glass felt like one small way to say thank you.
￼
The Laurel glass: made with gratitude for someone whose art and support mattered deeply.
Art Story
Esme’s Vigil Glass
When I heard Candace Musmeci — Esme Bramley — had been placed on vigil, I jumped on the opportunity. Years earlier, she was one of the people who made Ymir unforgettable for me. She has been a sounding board, a friend, and one of those people who already embodied the advice I like to give others: be the peer a newcomer needs to see.
She did not need the advice. She already was that person.
￼
Esme’s vigil glass — made for someone who has long been kindness in action.
Art Story
Nian Gao, China, and Making Space for Curiosity
The Nian Gao project was part food documentation, part cultural joy, part reminder that my path is allowed to be wide. I studied abroad in China, cooked with Chinese friends in college, came home still geeking out about food, history, and music, and eventually brought those interests into the SCA through classes and competition projects.
I am a fighter. But I also have those hyperfocus moments on food, culture, and bardic arts. Diversifying is fun sometimes. It does not take away from the field.
￼
Nian Gao and the wider truth behind it: Chinese culture, cooking, research, and giving myself permission to make things that matter to me.
Art Story
The Badge Project
This project moved from progress photos to a finished badge over weeks of tiny adjustments. I added lines, fought with the border, changed the edging, and kept going. When it was finally done, I wrote that it had been a fun project and a good way to keep my mind busy.
That matters. Not every project has to change the world. Some just have to carry you through the week.
￼
The finished badge project in green, silver, and black — stubborn work, frustration, and the quiet joy of finally getting it right.
Art Story
The First Song Scroll
I had wanted to do a scroll for a while and finally stopped waiting. I partnered with Adela Scrijver van Brugge and Tom Saucer and decided that if I was going to do this, I wanted to do it on glass. The first frame broke. A better one came later. The engraving bit wore down. The script fought me. I loved it anyway.
People realized that when I said I made a scroll, I did not mean calligraphy. I meant glass. A Song Scroll.
￼
The first Song Scroll — flaws, learning curves, collaboration, and the joy of making something I had talked about for a long time.
Art Story
“Am I Doing This Right?”
This was my “I need art right now to help my brain” project. I was able to use a photograph that is now Bill Bush’s profile picture and imagine what that image would look like in glass. That question — am I doing this right? — became the name of the piece.
Sometimes the answer is yes. Sometimes the answer is: keep making, keep learning, keep going.
￼
“Am I Doing This Right?” — one of those projects born from needing art in the middle of everything else.
Art Story
Memorial and Celebration in One Glass
This glass was made for a friend’s knighting and carried meaning from both me and Rodney Woods. I told David Stewart he was going to cry. He did not — but the piece still held a lot. It was a way of capturing a moment in time, and a reminder that some art pieces are gifts, and some are offerings of memory too.
￼
A glass made for a knighting, carrying celebration, friendship, and memory all at once.
Art Story
Elevation Gifts and Interkingdom Friendships
One of my favorite things about making art in the SCA is creating gifts for elevations. Every one of these pieces represents a relationship. Carson Reed inspired my first interkingdom practice, which grew into Borders Without Walls. Adela’s pitcher broke during travel, and she immediately saw beauty in how it might be repaired. That response alone explained why she deserved the Pelican.
Art becomes a way to say: I see who you are. I am glad you are here.
￼
Elevation gifts for people who shaped my life, my art, and the wider community around me.
